Unfortunately, this doesn't work in C++ because
```
static int x;
static int x = 0;
```
is not legal C++ code. Apparently, you cannot forward-declare variables in C++: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3714808/forward-declarations-for-variables

@egabancho I fully support the feature/use case of a user being able to save a deposit which doesn't validate according to your requirements. However, I'm not sure that allowing partial validation of the schema is what we want.

IMHO perhaps a deposit schema with reduced constraints could do the job? I consider the JSON  schema at the same level of say a db schema. It enforces a given minimal structure. I.e. it will not allow you to add keys which should not be there - if the db table doesn't allow you to save an ongoing deposit, then you should change the schema.

That said, we are clearly missing a best practice pattern for how to implement such a feature.

