@stonebig: `dill` can't do what `jupyter` has done, as the reason `python-prompt` works for them is that they have their own console they can modify -- so basically they append every line that is entered into their `jupyter` console to the `python_prompt` history instance.  If you are using the python interpreter (i.e. not `IPython`/`jupyter`), then that trick doesn't work.  `pyreadline` is the only good general solution on windows that I can find.  Yeah, it's end of life, but I don't foresee it going away at any time, and It's pure python should not be difficult to install.

